{"title":"Help","type":"markdown","params":{"fontSize":12,"markdown":"## Introduction
Welcome to the Security Onion Elastic Stack!  This is our implementation of the Elastic Stack on Security Onion.  The Elastic Stack consists of three primary components:
- `Elasticsearch` - stores logs
- `Logstash` - sends logs to Elasticsearch
- `Kibana` - web interface for visualizing logs

## Sidebar
Starting on the far left side of the page, you see the Sidebar.  This contains links such as:
- `Discover` - search data
- `Visualize` - create visualizations based on searches
- `Dashboard` - view or create dashboards based on visualizations
- `Timelion` - timeline analysis
- `Dev Tools` - query Elasticsearch directly
- `Management` - view or modify Kibana settings
- `Squert` - separate web interface for viewing NIDS and HIDS alerts
- `Logout` - log out of your session

The first six of those links are within Kibana itself.  If you click one of those and then want to get back to the Dashboards area where you started, simply click the `Dashboard` link.

Clicking the `Squert` link will take you out of Kibana and into Squert.

Clicking the `Logout` link will log you out of your session and take you back to the logon screen.

## Navigation Panel
When you are in the Kibana Dashboard area, the panel to the immediate right of the sidebar is the Navigation Panel and it includes links to our dashboards such as Home, Help (this page), Zeek Notices, ElastAlert, HIDS, NIDS, etc.  Clicking one of the links in the Navigation Panel will take you to a dashboard dedicated to that particular log type.  

## Dashboards
All dashboards are designed to work at 1024x768 screen resolution in order to maximize compatibility.

### Dashboard Hyperlinks

The `source_ip` and `destination_ip` fields are hyperlinked.  These hyperlinks will take you to the Indicator dashboard which will help you analyze the traffic relating to that particular IP address.

`UID` fields are also hyperlinked.  This hyperlink will start a new Kibana search for that particular UID.  In the case of Zeek UIDs this will show you all Zeek logs related to that particular connection.

Each log entry also has an `_id` field that is hyperlinked.  This hyperlink will take you to CapMe, allowing you to request full packet capture for any arbitrary log type.  This assumes that the log is for tcp or udp traffic that was seen by Zeek and Zeek recorded it correctly in its conn.log.  

### Overview Dashboard
When you first go to the Kibana Dashboard area, you are automatically placed into the Overview dashboard, where you will see overview information, such as total number of logs and sensors.  Use the information on the Overview dashboard to determine which of the other dashboards on the Navigation Panel you might want to visit next.

### Dashboard Categories
Our remaining dashboards are grouped into a few categories:
- `Alert Data` - dashboards that display alerts created by rules or signatures
- `Zeek Hunting` - dashboards that allow you to slice and dice network metadata for hunting
- `Host Hunting` - dashboards that allow you to hunt via host telemetry
- `Other` - dashboards that don't fit into the categories above

### Zeek Notices
Zeek sniffs network traffic and generates notices such as `SSL::Invalid Server Cert` and `TeamCymruMalwareHashRegistry::Match`.

### ElastAlert
ElastAlert queries Elasticsearch on a regular basis and then generates alerts based on your desired criteria.  Security Onion includes two example rules that alert on new IDS events and new connection logs.  You can add your own ElastAlert rules in `/etc/elastalert/rules/`.

### HIDS
Wazuh analyzes log files and generates Host Intrusion Detection System alerts based on its ruleset at `/var/ossec/rules/`.  You can add your own rules in `/var/ossec/rules/local_rules.xml`.  There is a separate OSSEC Dashboard below in the `Host Hunting` section which shows you all Wazuh logs including those logs that didn't generate HIDS alerts.

### NIDS
Security Onion can use either Snort or Suricata to sniff network traffic and generate Network Intrusion Detection System alerts.  

### Connections
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs connection metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, protocol, and number of bytes.

### DCE/RPC
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs DCE/RPC metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, operation, endpoint, and named pipe.

### DHCP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs DHCP requests and responses including source IP/port, destination IP/port, and MAC addresses.

### DNP3
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs DNP3 metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, function request, function reply.

### DNS
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs DNS queries and answers.  Zeek also includes other name lookups such as Windows NetBIOS name service requests and Bonjour.

### Files
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs metadata related to files being transferred over the network including IP addresses, MIME type, source, and checksums.

### FTP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs FTP metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, command, reply code, argument, and username.

### HTTP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs HTTP metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, method, status message, MIME type, site name, referer, and user agent.

### Intel
Zeek sniffs network traffic and watches for indicators using the Intel framework.  You can add your own indicators to `/opt/zeek/share/zeek/intel/intel.dat`.

### IRC
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs IRC metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, command, and username.

### Kerberos
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs Kerberos metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, cipher, client, server, service, request type, and success status.

### Modbus
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs Modbus metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, and function.

### MySQL
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs MySQL metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, command/argument, status, and response.

### NTLM
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs NTLM metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, hostname, username, and status.

### PE
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs PE metadata including OS, subsystem, machine, and section name.

### RADIUS
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs RADIUS metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, username, and result.

### RDP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs RDP metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, client build, keyboard layout, encryption level, and result.

### RFB
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs RFB metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, authentication method, authentication status, client version, server version, and desktop name.

### SIP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs SIP metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, method, content type, status, uri, and user agent.

### SMB
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs SMB metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, file name, and action.

### SMTP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs SMTP metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, from, to, subject, and user agent.

### SNMP
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs SNMP metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, version, community, and duration.

### Software
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs metadata relating to the kinds of software that generated that traffic including name, type, and version.

### SSH
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs SSH metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, client version, server version, and success.

### SSL
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs SSL metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, server name, certificate subject, cipher, and validation status.

### Syslog
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs Syslog metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, severity, and protocol.

### Tunnels
Zeek sniffs network traffic and detects IP, GRE, SOCKS, TEREDO, and AVAYA tunnels.  It logs metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, type, and action.

### Weird
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs protocol anomalies metadata including source IP/port, destination IP/port, and the type of anomaly.

### X.509
Zeek sniffs network traffic and logs X.509 metadata including certificate subject, issuer, key algorithm, key length, and signing algorithm.

### Autoruns
Sysinternals Autoruns can identify the processes which Windows is configured to automatically run.  Autoruns data can then be ingested via [Autoruns To WinEventLog](https://github.com/palantir/windows-event-forwarding/tree/master/AutorunsToWinEventLog).

### Beats
Elastic Beats can be deployed on endpoints to collect host telemetry and send to Logstash for storage in Elasticsearch.

### OSSEC
Wazuh has replaced OSSEC.  Wazuh agents can be deployed on endpoints to collect host telemetry and send to the Wazuh Server included in Security Onion.  HIDS Alerts can be found in the Alert Data category at the top of the Navigation Panel.  This Wazuh hunting dashboard will allow you to hunt through all Wazuh logs, not just alerts.

### Sysmon
Sysinternals Sysmon provides comprehensive telemetry for Windows hosts.  Its logs can be consumed using Beats, Wazuh, or other transport mechanism.

### Domain Stats
Security Onion includes a tool called domain_stats which will do a whois lookup on a domain name to determine the age of the domain.  If enabled, this dashboard looks for baby domains that have been recently registered.  Please note that domain_stats is only enabled when running in Evaluation Mode.

### Firewall
Firewall logs can be consumed via syslog or other transport mechanism.  Once consumed, this dashboard allows you to slice and dice those firewall logs based on source IP/port, destination IP/port, protocol, and action.

### Frequency
Security Onion includes a tool called freq_server which can perform frequency analysis of hostnames.  If enabled, this dashboard will show hostnames with a frequency analysis score that indicates that they could have been randomly generated.  Please note that freq_server is only enabled when running in Evaluation Mode.

### Stats
This dashboard shows statistics for Logstash including processing times for different log types and any errors that may have occurred.

## More Information
For additional information, please refer to our documentation at:

https://securityonion.net/docs/Elastic","type":"markdown"},"aggs":[]}
